title: Using mplush5
text: using functions package, need h5 file available. code shows use MplusAutomation run Mplus model. Note savedata option, “H5RESULTS” used specify h5 file.
code: mod <- MplusAutomation::mplusObject(   TITLE = "this is an example of a simple linear   regression for a continuous observed   dependent variable with two covariates",   MODEL = "y1 ON x1 x3;",   OUTPUT = "standardized; cinterval;",   SAVEDATA = "H5RESULTS = ex3_1.h5;",   rdata = ex3_1_df  )  MplusAutomation::mplusModeler(mod, modelout = "ex3_1.inp", run = 1)

title: Using mplush5
text: first function use mplus.view.results(). function lists available h5 function. Mplus writes different pieces information h5 file depending type model options specified, functions package can used every h5 file.
code: ex3_1 <- system.file("extdata", "ex3_1.h5", package = "mplush5") mplus.view.results(ex3_1) #>  #> Use the following functions to view the available results. #>  #>  - Input instructions #>   - mplus.print.input.instructions #>  - Summary of Analysis #>   - mplus.print.summary.analysis #>  - Model Fit Information #>   - mplus.print.model.fit.information #>  - Model Results #>   - mplus.print.model.results #>  - Confidence Intervals of Model Results #>   - mplus.print.confidence.intervals #>  - Standardized Model Results #>   - mplus.print.standardized.model.results #>  - Confidence Intervals of Standardized Model Results #>   - mplus.print.standardized.confidence.intervals #>  - R-Square #>   - mplus.print.rsquare

title: Using mplush5
text: mplus.view.results() function shows h5 file, following functions can used: mplus.print.input.instructions() mplus.print.summary.analysis() mplus.print.model.fit.information() mplus.print.model.results() mplus.print.confidence.intervals() mplus.print.standardized.model.results() mplus.print.standardized.confidence.intervals() mplus.print.rsquare() use functions just specify path h5 file. following code shows use mplus.print.model.results() function get model results.
code: ex3_1 <- system.file("extdata", "ex3_1.h5", package = "mplush5") results <- mplus.print.model.results(ex3_1) results #>              Section Statement  Estimate       S.E. Estimate/S.E. #> 1                     Y1 ON X1 0.9694732 0.04150770      23.35646 #> 2                     Y1 ON X3 0.6490355 0.04437483      14.62621 #> 3         Intercepts        Y1 0.5109621 0.04342922      11.76540 #> 4 Residual Variances        Y1 0.9412942 0.05953521      15.81072 #>   Two-Tailed P-Value #> 1                  0 #> 2                  0 #> 3                  0 #> 4                  0

title: Using mplush5
text: h5 file way access results Mplus. MplusAutomation package function readModels() reads parses Mplus output file. following code shows get information using readModels().
code: ex3_1.out <- system.file("extdata", "ex3_1.out", package = "mplush5") ex3_1_output <- MplusAutomation::readModels(ex3_1.out) ex3_1_output[["parameters"]][["unstandardized"]] #>          paramHeader param   est    se est_se pval #> 1              Y1.ON    X1 0.969 0.042 23.356    0 #> 2              Y1.ON    X3 0.649 0.044 14.626    0 #> 3         Intercepts    Y1 0.511 0.043 11.765    0 #> 4 Residual.Variances    Y1 0.941 0.060 15.811    0
